This monolithic monster is a Rolls-Royce 2021 Ghost: a two and a half ton slab of luxury. All delivered in a style that Rolls-Royce describes as ‘post-opulence’.

node.text: A wave of upcoming hypercars claim to accelerate 0 to 60 mph in as little as 1.7 seconds. However, nothing has been verified. The reality is that no production car has ever managed an official 0 to 60 time of under 2 seconds. There's a reason for that. We break down how current technology has created that limit, and what could be done to break it.

node.title: Why going 0 to 60 mph in under 2 seconds is almost impossible

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Tech Insider on September 20, 2021. May be an image of 1 person, standing and text that says 'prime amazon awud INSIDER Amazon's Al-powered cameras punish its delivery drivers when they look at side mirrors or when other cars cut them off, report says'.

node.text:
Amazon drivers are being punished for some driving habits that are considered safe and others that are beyond their control, Motherboard reported. 

Drivers told Motherboard that the AI-powered cameras in Amazon's delivery vans unfairly punished them for things such as looking at side mirrors, adjusting the radio, and even getting cut off in traffic by someone else. 

Whenever the cameras pick up on possible unsafe driving "events," these instances factor into workers' performance scores and can, in turn, hurt their chances of getting bonuses, extra pay, and prizes. 

Some Amazon drivers have resorted to covering up their vans' cameras with stickers to avoid getting unnecessary infractions. 

Click the link in our bio for more.

(Credit: Getty Images)

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Tech Insider on September 20, 2021. May be an image of ocean and text that says 'INSIDER Google and Facebook lay thousands of miles of undersea cables to ferry internet around the world. Here's how they do it.'.

node.text:
Google and Facebook have both laid thousands of miles of cables along the seafloor, stretching between continents, to carry internet around the world.

Laying these cables takes months of preparation, and specialized vessels take them out to sea. Once laid, the cables can ferry huge quantities of internet data around the globe.

Read more of Isobel Asher Hamilton's story at the link in our bio.

(Credit: Alcatel Submarine Networks; Google Cloud)

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Tech Insider on September 20, 2021. May be an image of ocean and text that says 'INSIDER Google and Facebook lay thousands of miles of undersea cables to ferry internet around the world. Here's how they do it.'.

Photo by Tech Insider on September 20, 2021. May be an image of body of water and text that says 'INSIDER Google is invested in 19 cable projects around the world. Facebook is invested in two currently active cables, and andis is involved in five more cable projects under construction, a spokesperson said.'.

Photo by Tech Insider on September 20, 2021. May be an image of outdoors and text that says 'INSIDER First, the companies have to plan the route they want the cable to take. Jayne Stowell, strategic negotiator for Global Infrastructure at Google, told Insider this step can take up to a year.'.

Photo by Tech Insider on September 20, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'The cable itself is about the thickness of a garden hose, Stowell said. Cables are wrapped in a copper casing for electricity conduction.'.
Photo by Tech Insider on September 20, 2021. May be an image of text.

Photo by Tech Insider on September 20, 2021. May be an image of outdoors and text that says 'INSIDER The vessel leaves port, spooling the cable behind it. Once it gets into deeper water, it deploys an underwater plow to dig a trench along the seabed into which it lays the cable.'.

Photo by Tech Insider on September 20, 2021. May be an image of 1 person, outdoors and text that says 'INSIDER SUBCOM For longer cables, Stowell said Google also installs a device called an amplifier every 100 meters (328 feet) to boost the signal and keep the data moving.'.
Photo by Tech Insider on September 20, 2021. May be an image of ocean and text.

Photo by Tech Insider on September 20, 2021. May be an image of outdoors and text that says 'AINSIDE PLANT HIRE R.T.C Finally, the cable is pulled up onto the beach to a ready-made trench, where it's connected to a beach manhole, a buried container where the undersea cable is hooked up to a terrestrial cable which in turn connects to a cable station.'.

Photo by Tech Insider on September 17, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'INSIDER Facebook spent the equivalent of 319 years labeling or removing false and misleading content posted in the US in 2020, according to a Wall Street Journal'.

node.text:
Facebook spent 2.8 million hours, or approximately 319 years, looking for false or misleading information on its platforms in the US in 2020.

A recent study found that posts with misinformation got six times more likes, shares, and interactions on Facebook compared to posts from more reputable news sources. 

Some content that was missed included gang violence, human trafficking, and drug cartels, according to the Wall Street Journal.

A spokesperson from Facebook told the Journal that the company also plans to look into artificial intelligence that will help them in its efforts against the spread of misinformation or violent content.

To read more, click the link in our bio.

Story by Emily Walsh.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Tech Insider on September 16, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Opinion INSIDER Our broken tech is fueling an environmental crisis Tech companies are sitting on the solution.'.

node.text:
For years, Apple has insisted that your iPhone is good for the planet. But the truth is, Insider contributing opinion author Katya Schwenk wrote, that smartphones have a serious environmental toll.

iPhones, like most smartphones run on lithium ion batteries — manufactured with precious metals mined from Tibetan grasslands, the salt flats of Chile, and, soon, the Salton Sea in California. The waste from these mines is poisonous and leaches into surrounding communities. Lithium extraction requires enormous quantities of water and eats up local water supply.

And every day, instead of repairing their broken phones, consumers discard hundreds of thousands of smartphones, which then join the billions of tons of electronic waste that flows into landfills, the ocean, and city streets. 

Consumers aren’t merely replacing iPhones to get the newest version though; Tech giants are making their devices nearly impossible to fix, for both independent repair shops and DIY tinkerers. And this is keeping the industry booming.

Click the link in our bio for more.

Story by Katy Schwenk.

(Credit: Marianne Ayala/Insider)

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Tech Insider on September 16, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Opinion INSIDER Our broken tech is fueling an environmental crisis Tech companies are sitting on the solution.'.

Photo by Tech Insider on September 16, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'INSIDER Tech heading to landfills at a rapid pace Every day, instead of repairing their broken phones, consumers discard hundreds of thousands of smartphones, which then join the billions of tons of electronic waste that flow into landfills, the ocean, and city streets. Consumer tech manufacturers have, gradually, made smartphones more intimidating to repair. This ensures that tech is difficult to fix, for both independent repair shops and DIY tinkerers.'.

Photo by Tech Insider on September 16, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'INSIDER The 'right to repair' movement As the pandemic filled emergency rooms, ventilators began to break. And hospitals were not able to fix them: They were constrained by the whims of medical tech manufacturers, which frequently keep repair instructions from the public, forcing hospitals to consult "authorized' repair technicians, even when on-site staff were qualified to do so. It became a metaphor for the ways that consumers are being held hostage by tech companies, all for the sake of revenue.'.

Photo by Tech Insider on September 16, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'INSIDER Increasingly computerized For years, farmers have warred with John Deere, a tractor and machinery manufacturer, to allow them to fix their equipment without heading to the dealer. John Deere has been unrelenting. Like John Deere's tractors, our cars, tools, and household appliances are wired with impenetrable software that consumers are prevented from fixing. The use of software might make the machines more modern, but it also renders them more controllable by the manufacturer.'.

Photo by Tech Insider on September 16, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'INSIDER Change on the horizon Last month, President Biden signed an executive order that announced his support for better consumer protections for repairs, directing the Federal Trade Commission to consider new enforcement on the issue. And a few weeks ago, the FTC voted unanimously to better enforce laws around the right to repair. It was, as Nathan Proctor, a repair advocate, wrote: big day for the right to fix our stuff." It was a big day, too, for the fight for a greener economy.'.

node.text:
Oura's CEO said his company's ring was popular among employers bringing workers back to the office. After trying out a smart ring for two weeks, I don't think that strategy will be effective.

(Credit: Meghan Herborth/Insider)

node.accessibility_caption: A graphic shows an image of the author holding her and up with an Oura smart ring on her middle finger. It reads: Premium. I wore Oura's smart ring for 2 weeks to track my sleep and temperature. Here's why I couldn't wait to ditch Silicon Valley's favorite wearable.

A graphic shows an image of the Oura Ring test sizing kit with 8 different sample sizes. It reads: First, I received a sizing kit for my Oura Ring. I ended up ordering a size 9 but could not wait to get that plastic ring off my finger. It was hard to test the different sizes because, as I learned, plastic is extremely hard to slip off your finger if and when you figure out it's too small.

A graphic shows the Oura ring and the packaging. It reads: A week later, my Oura ring arrived. The ring weighs less than five pennies and tracks a person's vital signs like temperature and heart rate from its perch on their finger.
It isn't considered a medical-grade device by the Food and Drug Administration.

A graphic shows the Oura ring in its wireless charging station on top of a nightstand. It reads: It took time to adjust to wearing the ring, especially to sleep.I struggled throughout the two weeks to get used to the thickness of the band itself, which definitely seems suited for people with larger hands than I have.

A graphic shows a screenshot of the Oura ring sleep data on the left and a screenshot of the Garmin Instinct watch sleep data on the right. It reads: The breakdown of my night's sleep was highly specific and usually tracked well with how I felt in the morning. The data from my Garmin Instinct watch is much less detailed. I found both devices collected roughly the same data and came to the same conclusions — I need better sleep.

A graphic shows an image of the author holding a mug with the Oura smart ring on her middle finger. It reads: Once my two-week trial was done, I took the ring off and haven't missed it. 
It doesn't allow for much change in finger size throughout the day. I most looked forward to tracking my temperature, and I was disappointed to find that it didn't proactively alert me to changes throughout the day.

node.text:
Apple just unveiled new versions of many of its biggest products on Tuesday, including the iPhone 13. 

New versions of the iPad, iPad Mini, and Apple Watch were also debuted.

With the exception of a design update to the iPad Mini, none of the product updates featured major changes. Click the link in our bio to read more.

Stories by Ben Gilbert, Avery Hartmans, and Antonio Villas-Boas.

(Credit: Apple)
#iphone13 #appleevent #apple #iphone

Apple is warning users to update their devices as soon as possible after it fixed a major spyware flaw.

The company has released emergency software updates in iOS 14.8 after learning of a vulnerability that let hackers break into Apple devices without users even clicking a link, The New York Times reports.

"Apple is aware of a report that this issue may have been actively exploited," the company said on its website Monday.

For more info, click the link in our bio.

Story by Sarah Jackson.

[Credit: MLADEN ANTONOV/Getty Images]

node.text:
Grigory Yakushev was fired from Google six years ago after a steep drop in productivity.

He said he thought he’d burned out but later found out it was undiagnosed depression. He shared his advice for dealing with burnout and mental health in the tech industry.

Click the link in our bio and subscribe to Insider to read Yakushev’s story.

(Credit: Grigory Yakushev)

node.accessibility_caption: Photo of Yakushev with the headline, "I was fired from Google after 5 years as a software engineer. It turned out to be good for my career and mental health, but here's what I should've done sooner."

Text graphic with the text, "I was fired from Google six years ago after a steep drop in productivity. I was fired from Google in April 2015, after nearly five years of working in the office in Zurich, Switzerland. I had experienced burnout about a year before that. I was eventually put on a performance-improvement plan. After a week, it was quite obvious to me that I wasn't going to be successful. I was spending my day staring at the screen. They gave me a termination notice the next week."

Text graphic with the text, "Looking back, one thing I should've done sooner is see a doctor. When I finally contacted a doctor, I was quickly diagnosed with depression. I was put on medication and started therapy. Depression drains our motivation, including the motivation to get a diagnosis. But that's crucial to starting treatment and recovery."

Text graphic with the text, "Google is a honey trap, in my opinion. The pay is good. You're surrounded by incredibly smart people. There are snacks on hand. And the (generally) reduced level of bullshit makes it a nice place to stay. So we stay and submit our 0.1% improvements to search quality every couple of months. But burning out forced me to move around and to think about my own mind and how it works. It's been six years since I was fired from Google, and I can say it was definitely a fortunate event in my life."
